                <li>Export results as CSV or copy them with one click.</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>What is a hash function?</h2>
              <p>
                A <strong>hash function</strong> is a one-way function that maps
                data of arbitrary size to a fixed-size output called a
                <em>hash</em> or <em>digest</em>. Cryptographic hash functions
                are designed to have these properties:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Deterministic</strong> – the same input always
                  produces the same hash.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Preimage resistance</strong> – given a hash, it should
                  be infeasible to find an input that produces it.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Second-preimage resistance</strong> – given one input,
                  it should be hard to find a different input with the same
                  hash.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Collision resistance</strong> – it should be hard to
                  find any two different inputs with the same hash.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Common hash algorithms</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>MD5</strong> – 128-bit hash. Fast and widely
                  supported, but broken for security; use only for legacy
                  checksums.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>SHA-1</strong> – 160-bit hash. Also broken for
                  security; avoid for new designs.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>SHA-2 family</strong> – includes SHA-224, SHA-256,
                  SHA-384, SHA-512. Currently considered secure when used
                  correctly.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>SHA-3 family</strong> – newer standard based on
                  Keccak; includes SHA3-256 and SHA3-512.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>RIPEMD-160</strong> – 160-bit hash used in some
                  blockchain and PGP contexts.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Hashes vs HMAC vs password hashing</h2>
              <h3>Plain hash</h3>
              <p>
                A plain hash is just <code>hash(message)</code>. Anyone can
                compute it. It is suitable for:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  File integrity checks (e.g., comparing download hashes).
                </li>
                <li>Deduplication and quick equality checks.</li>
                <li>Non-security-sensitive fingerprints.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>HMAC (keyed hash)</h3>
              <p>
                An HMAC (Hash-based Message Authentication Code) uses a secret
                key:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code
                  >HMAC(key, message) = hash((key ⊕ opad) ∥ hash((key ⊕ ipad) ∥
                  message))</code
                >
              </div>
              <p>
                Only someone with the key can generate or verify the HMAC, so it
                provides both integrity and authenticity.
              </p>

              <h3>Password hashing</h3>
              <p>
                Passwords should <strong>not</strong> be stored with a single
                fast hash like MD5 or SHA-256. Instead, use a
                <strong>slow, memory-hard</strong> algorithm such as:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>bcrypt</strong></li>
                <li><strong>scrypt</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Argon2</strong> (Argon2id recommended)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                These algorithms use a per-password salt and a cost factor to
                make brute-force attacks much more expensive. This tool can
                demonstrate salted and iterated hashing, but it is not a full
                password-hashing implementation.
              </p>

              <h2>Salt and iterations</h2>
              <p>
                A <strong>salt</strong> is random data combined with the input
                before hashing, typically:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>hash = H( salt ∥ password )</code>
              </div>
              <p>
                Iterating the hash many times increases the cost of guessing
                attacks:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>h<sub>0</sub> = H(salt ∥ password)</code><br />
                <code>h<sub>i+1</sub> = H(h<sub>i</sub>)</code> for
                <code>i = 0 … n-1</code>
              </div>
              <p>
                In this generator you can experiment with salts and iteration
                counts to see how the resulting hashes change.
              </p>

              <h2>Security notes</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This tool runs entirely in your browser; no hashing data is
                  sent to the server.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Do not rely on MD5 or SHA-1 for new security-sensitive
                  systems.
                </li>
                <li>
                  For password storage, use dedicated password-hashing libraries
                  (bcrypt, scrypt, Argon2) on your server.
                </li>
                <li>Always use HTTPS when working with any sensitive data.</li>
              </ul>
